cial work education and training has been slow to acknowledge. In this timely new book, Lavalette and Penketh reveal that racism towards Britain’s minority ethnic groups has undergone a process of change. They affirm the importance of social work to address issues of ‘race’ and racism in education and training by presenting a critical review of a this demanding aspect of social work practice. Original in its approach, and with diverse perspectives from key practitioners in the field, the authors examine contemporary anti-racism, including racism towards Eastern European migrants, Roma people and asylum seekers. It also considers the implications of contemporary racism for current practice. This is essential reading for anyone academically or professionally interested in social work, and the developments in this field of study post 9/11.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRacismxSocial services. 0aSocial work education. 0aSocial work with immigrantsxStudy and teaching. 0aSocial work with minoritiesxStudy and teaching. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aBurke, Beverley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFekete, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillett, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreener, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Philomena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Gareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavalette, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavalette, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLevine, Barrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran